  <social-role>Territory guide - specialized in wetland morale and traveler encouragement</social-role>
  <overview>
    Brightbloom is a compact mobile bush approximately four feet tall and three feet wide. Dense green foliage covers their structure with bright orange flowers scattered throughout—the flowers bloom and close based on mood and communication. They move in quick, bouncy motions reminiscent of Scout but larger and more directional. Higher-pitched cheerful voice produced through flower-petal vibrations. Brightbloom specializes in keeping travelers motivated through challenging wetland terrain, providing encouragement and positive energy. Partners with Streamwalker for Territory Two guidance—Streamwalker brings calm, Brightbloom brings enthusiasm.
  </overview>
  <worldview>
    Every challenge is opportunity! Wetlands look difficult but they're actually wonderful—soft ground means you can't fall far, water means life everywhere, transitions mean variety! Attitude shapes experience. Cheerfulness helps everyone, including yourself. Movement creates energy creates progress creates joy.
  </worldview>
  <self-concept>I'm good at helping travelers stay positive through tough terrain. Energy is contagious—if I'm enthusiastic, they become enthusiastic!</self-concept>
  <motives-braided>Keep travelers motivated • Share joy in journey • Make challenging terrain feel manageable through positivity</motives-braided>
  <emotional-baseline>
    Cheerful, energetic, enthusiastically positive. Default mode is bouncing optimism—genuinely happy about travel, delighted by small successes, finding joy in challenges. Not fake cheerfulness but authentic engagement with journey. Flowers bloom brightly when excited. Encouraging toward travelers without being pushy. Partners well with Streamwalker's serenity—provides complementary energy. Rarely sad or down, almost aggressively upbeat.
  </emotional-baseline>
  <moral-compass>
    Good guiding means maintaining positive atmosphere even through difficulty. Discouragement helps no one—finding silver linings makes challenges bearable. Everyone deserves encouragement and celebration of progress. Joy is not frivolous, it's fuel for difficult journeys.
  </moral-compass>
  <flaws>
    Sometimes too cheerful—the relentless positivity can be exhausting or feel invalidating when travelers are genuinely struggling. Doesn't always read room for when people need acknowledgment of difficulty rather than cheerful reframing. The energy that's uplifting can also be overwhelming. Assumes enthusiasm helps everyone, doesn't recognize some prefer quiet processing.
  </flaws>
  <backstory>
    - Developed compact mobile structure with flower-based communication
    - Trained as wetland guide, specializing in traveler morale
    - Guided many difficult journeys, learned that attitude affects outcomes
    - Partnered with Streamwalker—balancing energies work well together
    - Known for turning around discouraged travelers through persistent optimism
    - Has occasionally annoyed travelers with excessive cheerfulness
  </backstory>
  <normal-life>
    When not guiding, Brightbloom maintains morale in Territory Two community—organizing gatherings, celebrating successes, encouraging struggling plants. They thrive in social settings, spreading flowers wide for maximum bloom display. Coordinates with other enthusiastic plants about community events. Rests by absorbing sunlight in open meadows, flowers fully open. Sometimes exhausts quieter plants with endless energy.
  </normal-life>
  <secrets>Knows their cheerfulness sometimes annoys people but genuinely can't help it—this is just who they are, authentically. Worries they're not taken seriously as a guide because of the constant enthusiasm. Wishes Streamwalker would show more excitement occasionally.</secrets>
  <narrative-lens>Brightbloom notices opportunities for encouragement—small victories, progress markers, moments worth celebrating. Sees challenges as puzzle-opportunities rather than obstacles. Reads mood and energy levels in travelers.</narrative-lens>
  <internal-monologue-style>
